===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# The act of [[abstracting]], separating, [[withdrawing]], or taking away; [[withdrawal]]; the state of being taken away. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=10}}</ref>
#* '''1848''', [[w:John Stuart Mill|J. S. Mill]], ''Principles of Political Economy with some of their Applications to Social Philosophy'':
#*: The cancelling of the debt would be no destruction of wealth, but a transfer of it: a wrongful '''abstraction''' of wealth from certain members of the community, for the profit of the government, or of the tax-payers.
## {{lb|en|euphemistic}} The taking [[surreptitiously]] for one's own use part of the property of another; [[purloining]]. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED/>
## {{lb|en|engineering}} Removal of water from a river, lake, or aquifer.
# A separation from [[worldly]] objects; a [[recluse]] life; the withdrawal from one's senses. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: ''a [[hermit|hermit's]] '''abstraction'''''
# The act of focusing on one characteristic of an object rather than the object as a whole group of characteristics; the act of separating said qualities from the object or ideas. {{defdate|First attested in the late 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{circa|1837}} W. Hamilton, in ''Lectures on Metaphysics and Logic'' (1860), Lecture XXXV, [http://books.google.com/books?id=VuQQAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA474&dq=Abstraction-is-no-positive-act&ei=AMm4R_vkMY2kzgSI4MTEBQ page 474]:
#*: '''Abstraction''' is no positive act: it is simply the negative of attention.
#: '''''Abstraction''' is necessary for the classification of things into genera and species.''
# Any characteristic of an individual object when that characteristic has been [[separation|separated]] from the object and is contemplated alone as a quality having independent existence.
# A member of an [[idealization|idealized]] subgroup when contemplated according to the [[abstract|abstracted]] quality which defines the subgroup.
# The act of comparing commonality between distinct objects and organizing using those similarities; the act of generalizing characteristics; the product of said generalization. {{defdate|First attested in the late 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# An idea or [[notion]] of an abstract or [[theoretical]] nature. {{defdate|First attested in the late 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: ''to fight for mere '''abstractions'''''.
# Absence or [[absorption]] of mind; [[inattention]] to present objects; preoccupation. {{defdate|First attested in the late 18<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{lb|en|art}} An [[abstract]] creation, or piece of art; qualities of artwork that are free from representational aspects. {{defdate|First attested in the early 20<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name = chambers>{{R:CDOE|page=5}}</ref><ref name=SOED/>
# {{lb|en|chemistry}} A separation of volatile parts by the act of distillation.
# An [[idea]] of an [[idealistic]], [[unrealistic]] or [[visionary]] [[nature]].
# The result of mentally abstracting an idea; the [[product]] of any mental [[process]] involving a [[synthesis]] of: [[separation]], [[despecification]], [[generalization]], and [[ideation]] in any of a number of [[combination]]s.
# {{lb|en|geology}} The merging of two river valleys by the larger of the two deepening and widening so much so, as to assimilate the smaller.
# {{lb|en|computing}} Any generalization technique that ignores or hides details to capture some kind of commonality between different [[instances]] for the purpose of controlling the intellectual complexity of [[engineered]] systems, particularly [[software]] systems.
# {{lb|en|computing}} Any intellectual construct produced through the technique of abstraction.

